# ============================================================
# CHUNK 1: Data import + preparation (2024)
# - Automated Traffic Volume Counts (7ym2-wayt): borough-day traffic
# - 311 Service Requests (erm2-nwe9): borough-day noise complaints
# Output objects:
#   traffic_2024, noise_2024, panel_2024_A
# ============================================================

# install.packages(c("httr2","jsonlite","dplyr","lubridate","readr","tibble","tidyr"))

library(httr2)
library(jsonlite)
library(dplyr)
library(lubridate)
library(readr)
library(tibble)
library(tidyr)

# Optional Socrata App Token (recommended if you hit rate limits)
# Sys.setenv(SODA_APP_TOKEN = "YOUR_APP_TOKEN_HERE")

soda_get <- function(endpoint, query, app_token = Sys.getenv("SODA_APP_TOKEN", "")) {
  req <- request(endpoint) |> req_url_query(!!!query)
  if (nzchar(app_token)) req <- req |> req_headers(`X-App-Token` = app_token)
  resp <- req |> req_perform()
  txt  <- resp |> resp_body_string()
  fromJSON(txt, flatten = TRUE) |> as_tibble()
}

std_boro <- function(x) toupper(trimws(x))

# -----------------------------
# 1) TRAFFIC (2024) -> borough-day
# Dataset: 7ym2-wayt
# -----------------------------
traffic_2024 <- soda_get(
  "https://data.cityofnewyork.us/resource/7ym2-wayt.json",
  list(
    `$select` = paste(
      "boro, yr, m, d,",
      "sum(vol) as traffic_vol,",
      "count(*) as records"
    ),
    `$where`  = "yr = 2024 AND vol IS NOT NULL AND vol >= 0",
    `$group`  = "boro, yr, m, d",
    `$limit`  = 200000
  )
) |>
  mutate(
    yr = as.integer(yr),
    m  = as.integer(m),
    d  = as.integer(d),
    date = as.Date(sprintf("%04d-%02d-%02d", yr, m, d)),
    borough = std_boro(boro),
    traffic_vol = parse_number(traffic_vol),
    records = as.integer(parse_number(records)),
    traffic_per_record = traffic_vol / pmax(records, 1L)
  ) |>
  select(borough, date, traffic_vol, records, traffic_per_record) |>
  arrange(borough, date)

# -----------------------------
# 2) 311 NOISE (2024) -> borough-day
# Dataset: erm2-nwe9
# Complaint types: Noise - Street/Sidewalk, Noise - Vehicle
# -----------------------------
noise_2024 <- soda_get(
  "https://data.cityofnewyork.us/resource/erm2-nwe9.json",
  list(
    `$select` = "borough, date_trunc_ymd(created_date) as date, count(*) as noise_complaints",
    `$where`  = paste(
      "created_date >= '2024-01-01T00:00:00.000'",
      "AND created_date <  '2025-01-01T00:00:00.000'",
      "AND complaint_type IN ('Noise - Street/Sidewalk','Noise - Vehicle')",
      "AND borough IS NOT NULL"
    ),
    `$group`  = "borough, date",
    `$limit`  = 200000
  )
) |>
  mutate(
    date = as.Date(date),
    borough = std_boro(borough),
    noise_complaints = as.integer(parse_number(noise_complaints))
  ) |>
  select(borough, date, noise_complaints) |>
  arrange(borough, date)

# -----------------------------
# 3) OPTION A PANEL (analysis-ready)
# Keep ONLY traffic-observed days (no fake traffic zeros).
# Fill missing noise to 0 (no complaints that day in that borough).
# Add readable day-of-week factor.
# -----------------------------
panel_2024_A <- traffic_2024 |>
  left_join(noise_2024, by = c("borough", "date")) |>
  mutate(
    noise_complaints = if_else(is.na(noise_complaints), 0L, noise_complaints),
    dow = factor(wday(date, label = TRUE, week_start = 1), ordered = FALSE)
  ) |>
  filter(borough %in% c("BRONX","BROOKLYN","MANHATTAN","QUEENS","STATEN ISLAND")) |>
  arrange(borough, date)

# Quick sanity checks (so you can describe data coverage in your report)
coverage_check <- panel_2024_A |>
  group_by(borough) |>
  summarise(
    traffic_days = n(),
    date_min = min(date),
    date_max = max(date),
    .groups = "drop"
  )

print(coverage_check)

# ============================================================
# CHUNK 2: Analysis answering the question
# "Do higher traffic volumes correlate with more noise complaints across boroughs?"
# Outputs:
#   corr_table_df (clean correlation summary)
#   p_scatter (nice facet scatter)
#   p_weekly  (weekly trends)
#   p_corrbar (easy correlation bars)
#   model_dow (interpretable regression)
# ============================================================

# install.packages(c("ggplot2","scales"))
library(ggplot2)
library(scales)
library(dplyr)
library(lubridate)
library(tidyr)

MIN_DAYS <- 30  # quality threshold for correlation reporting

# Correlation summary (use normalized traffic_per_record for readability)
corr_table_df <- panel_2024_A |>
  group_by(borough) |>
  summarise(
    n_days = n(),
    corr_total = if_else(n_days < MIN_DAYS, NA_real_,
                        cor(traffic_vol, noise_complaints, use = "complete.obs")),
    corr_norm  = if_else(n_days < MIN_DAYS, NA_real_,
                        cor(traffic_per_record, noise_complaints, use = "complete.obs")),
    .groups = "drop"
  ) |>
  arrange(borough)

print(corr_table_df)

# ---- Plot A (best “clean look”): facet scatter with normalized traffic ----
# (Drop Staten Island in visuals because it usually has too few traffic days.)
plot_df <- panel_2024_A |>
  filter(borough != "STATEN ISLAND")

p_scatter <- ggplot(plot_df, aes(x = traffic_per_record, y = noise_complaints)) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.35, size = 1.8) +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE, linewidth = 1) +
  facet_wrap(~ borough, scales = "free_y") +
  labs(
    title = "Traffic vs Noise Complaints by Borough (2024)",
    subtitle = "Traffic-observed days only • Traffic normalized by # of traffic records (traffic_per_record)",
    x = "Traffic per record (traffic_vol / records)",
    y = "Noise complaints (Noise - Street/Sidewalk + Noise - Vehicle)"
  ) +
  theme_minimal(base_size = 13)

p_scatter

# ---- Plot B: weekly trends (easiest “story” plot) ----
weekly <- plot_df |>
  mutate(week = floor_date(date, "week", week_start = 1)) |>
  group_by(borough, week) |>
  summarise(
    weekly_noise = sum(noise_complaints, na.rm = TRUE),
    weekly_traffic = mean(traffic_per_record, na.rm = TRUE),
    .groups = "drop"
  ) |>
  pivot_longer(cols = c(weekly_noise, weekly_traffic),
               names_to = "metric", values_to = "value") |>
  mutate(metric = recode(metric,
                         weekly_noise = "Weekly noise complaints (sum)",
                         weekly_traffic = "Weekly traffic per record (mean)"))

p_weekly <- ggplot(weekly, aes(x = week, y = value)) +
  geom_line(linewidth = 0.9) +
  facet_grid(metric ~ borough, scales = "free_y") +
  labs(
    title = "Weekly Trends: Noise vs Traffic (2024)",
    subtitle = "Cleaner than daily scatter for comparing movement over time",
    x = "Week",
    y = NULL
  ) +
  theme_minimal(base_size = 12)

p_weekly

# ---- Plot C: correlation bars (super easy to interpret) ----
corr_plot <- corr_table_df |>
  filter(!is.na(corr_norm))  # apply MIN_DAYS threshold

p_corrbar <- ggplot(corr_plot, aes(x = reorder(borough, corr_norm), y = corr_norm)) +
  geom_col(alpha = 0.85) +
  coord_flip() +
  geom_text(aes(label = paste0("r=", round(corr_norm, 2), " (n=", n_days, ")")),
            hjust = ifelse(corr_plot$corr_norm >= 0, -0.05, 1.05),
            size = 4) +
  expand_limits(y = c(min(corr_plot$corr_norm, 0) - 0.1, max(corr_plot$corr_norm, 0) + 0.1)) +
  labs(
    title = "Correlation: Traffic vs Noise Complaints (2024)",
    subtitle = "Using normalized traffic_per_record • Traffic-observed days only",
    x = NULL,
    y = "Correlation (r)"
  ) +
  theme_minimal(base_size = 13)

# ---- Regression (interpretable): day-of-week is a normal factor now ----
# (Uses normalized traffic so it’s not dominated by extreme totals.)
model_dow <- lm(noise_complaints ~ traffic_per_record + borough + dow, data = plot_df)
summary(model_dow)
